        "cooked": "<p>there‚Äôs quite a lot of explanation for why people prefer there being a public edit history in this thread:</p><aside class=\"quote quote-modified\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"975\">\n  <div class=\"title\">\n    <div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n    <img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/db5fbb/48.png\" class=\"avatar\">\n    <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/edit-sent-messages/975\">Edit sent messages</a> <a class=\"badge-category__wrapper \" href=\"/c/feature-requests/17\"><span data-category-id=\"17\" style=\"--category-badge-color: #83B72A; --category-badge-text-color: #FFFFFF;\" data-drop-close=\"true\" class=\"badge-category \" title=\"Post your ideas here for new features and functionality for the Signal app.\"><span class=\"badge-category__name\">Feature Requests</span></span></a>\n  </div>\n  <blockquote>\n    Two of the most common and awkward UX issues in any text messaging service are: \n\nnot noticing a typo, or reconsidering the phrasing, in your message until after you sent it. This is a problem users of email, SMS, and Internet chat services run into every day. It‚Äôs so much nicer when you actually edit the message to fix the typos, correct the phrasing, or whatever ‚Äì like in Discourse forum posts. I wish Signal could do this.\naccidentally messaging the wrong person. This issue is at best just a l‚Ä¶\n  </blockquote>\n</aside>\n",
